SIMPLE: salvage
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Salvage
<hw>Sal"vage</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>salvage</ets>, OF. <ets>salver</ets> to save, F. <ets>sauver</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>salvare</ets>. See <er>Save</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of saving a vessel, goods, or life, from perils of the
sea.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Salvage</qex> of life from a British ship, or a foreign ship
in British waters, ranks before <qex>salvage</qex> of goods.</q>
<rj><qau>Encyc. Brit.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Maritime Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The
compensation allowed to persons who voluntarily assist in saving a ship
or her cargo from peril.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>That part of the
property that survives the peril and is saved.</def> <rj><au>Kent.
Abbot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salvage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Salvage
<hw>Sal"vage</hw>, <pos>a. & n.</pos> <def>Savage.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salvation</ent>⟦br⟧
